00:29:47.460 --> 00:29:52.290
One way is to put the four
fluorines into play

00:29:52.290 --> 00:29:55.000
and then I have the--

00:29:55.000 --> 00:29:57.000
these are called lone pairs.

00:29:57.000 --> 00:29:57.850
Why are they lone?

00:29:57.850 --> 00:30:00.030
Because they don't
bond to a second.

00:30:00.030 --> 00:30:04.040
So sometimes chemists call
these lone pairs.

00:30:04.040 --> 00:30:05.490
They're all alone.

00:30:05.490 --> 00:30:08.280
It's Friday and all alone.

00:30:08.280 --> 00:30:09.920
So here they are.

00:30:09.920 --> 00:30:12.830
So that's one way to put them,
but there's another way to put

00:30:12.830 --> 00:30:15.660
them, and that's
this one here.

00:30:15.660 --> 00:30:18.700
I'm going to go way over
to the other side, and

00:30:18.700 --> 00:30:20.290
here's the other way.

00:30:20.290 --> 00:30:24.660
The other way to put them is to
put the pairs in the same

00:30:24.660 --> 00:30:30.480
plane next to each other,
