00:38:36.700 --> 00:38:38.830
And how about the energetics?

00:38:38.830 --> 00:38:40.140
How do we get five of these?

00:38:40.140 --> 00:38:43.350
If we've got five struts, it
means we must have five

00:38:43.350 --> 00:38:46.690
hybridized orbitals
of equal energy.

00:38:46.690 --> 00:38:51.230
Well, we got six before and
before that, we had four.

00:38:51.230 --> 00:38:52.800
Before that, we had three.

00:38:52.800 --> 00:38:53.980
Well, now we're going
to get five.

00:38:53.980 --> 00:38:57.230
So how do we make
five orbitals?

00:38:57.230 --> 00:38:59.180
So in this case I start--

00:38:59.180 --> 00:39:08.370
I want s, p, d, and
I want five.

00:39:08.370 --> 00:39:12.190
So one plus three is four
plus one is five and

00:39:12.190 --> 00:39:14.660
that gives me sp3d.

00:39:17.790 --> 00:39:22.560
Gives me five and then,
what do we got?

00:39:22.560 --> 00:39:24.480
One, two, three.

00:39:24.480 --> 00:39:26.050
It's good.

00:39:26.050 --> 00:39:26.730
OK.

00:39:26.730 --> 00:39:29.210
Now--

00:39:29.210 --> 00:39:30.750
so we've covered a lot.

00:39:30.750 --> 00:39:31.050
All right.

00:39:31.050 --> 00:39:33.330
So some parting comments.

00:39:33.330 --> 00:39:35.200
We've been sticking other
things-- what we could do is

00:39:35.200 --> 00:39:39.230
we could do this one.

00:39:39.230 --> 00:39:41.670
We could take carbon and I'm
going to go now sp3.

00:39:44.470 --> 00:39:46.330
only instead of putting
hydrogens, I'm going to put

00:39:46.330 --> 00:39:48.040
carbons here.

00:39:48.040 --> 00:39:49.190
So what happens now?

00:39:49.190 --> 00:39:51.450
One, two, three, four.

00:39:51.450 --> 00:39:52.870
I'll put another carbon here.

00:39:52.870 --> 00:39:55.620
One, two, three, four,
et cetera.

00:39:55.620 --> 00:40:03.530
So this is sp3, all carbon, and
this is called diamond.

00:40:03.530 --> 00:40:06.180
This is called diamond sp3.

00:40:06.180 --> 00:40:08.930
So these are all sigma
bonds, all sigma

00:40:08.930 --> 00:40:12.490
bonds everywhere, sp3.

00:40:12.490 --> 00:40:15.733
And these are very, very strong
bonds and these are

00:40:15.733 --> 00:40:18.660
very tight bonds-- and one of
the properties of diamond is

00:40:18.660 --> 00:40:24.400
that it has a very high
refractive index

00:40:24.400 --> 00:40:25.690
because high energy--

00:40:25.690 --> 00:40:27.790
and these are tight,
tight bonds.

00:40:27.790 --> 00:40:28.975
So the electrons aren't
easily excited.

00:40:28.975 --> 00:40:31.410
It's transparent, divisible
light, which means that when

00:40:31.410 --> 00:40:33.880
light shines on this, there's
no expectation,

00:40:33.880 --> 00:40:35.500
but there is bending.

00:40:35.500 --> 00:40:38.060
So it's very, very high
refractive index and a high

00:40:38.060 --> 00:40:41.170
refractive index is what makes
this such a troublesome

00:40:41.170 --> 00:40:43.270
compound because it concentrates
light.

00:40:43.270 --> 00:40:46.530
So you can imagine there's
somebody in a dimly lit cafe,

00:40:46.530 --> 00:40:49.690
and she's sitting over in the
corner with a candle in front,

00:40:49.690 --> 00:40:52.130
and she's wearing a diamond
stud, and it takes those few

00:40:52.130 --> 00:40:53.510
candellas of energy.

00:40:53.510 --> 00:40:56.030
It concentrates, it shoots
it in the room, and some

00:40:56.030 --> 00:40:59.210
unsuspecting fellow gets hit
in the eye, is attracted to

00:40:59.210 --> 00:41:01.610
the person wearing the earrings,
and that's when the

00:41:01.610 --> 00:41:04.060
trouble begins.

00:41:04.060 --> 00:41:07.850
So this is very, very dangerous,
very dangerous, and

00:41:07.850 --> 00:41:11.690
it's a consequence of these
strong sigma bonds.

00:41:11.690 --> 00:41:13.770
But there's another way.

00:41:13.770 --> 00:41:16.260
There's another way that
we can bond carbon.

00:41:16.260 --> 00:41:19.550
We can make sp2 hybrids.

00:41:19.550 --> 00:41:22.280
So if we make sp2 hybrids,
that now looks like this.

00:41:22.280 --> 00:41:26.500
The carbon lies in the plane,
120 degrees, which means we're

00:41:26.500 --> 00:41:32.330
going to end up with something
that looks like this, et

00:41:32.330 --> 00:41:33.650
cetera, et cetera.

00:41:33.650 --> 00:41:36.100
And this is graphite.

00:41:36.100 --> 00:41:38.150
This is graphite.

00:41:38.150 --> 00:41:41.400
And now we have a mix of sigma
bonds in the plane that are

00:41:41.400 --> 00:41:42.090
very strong.

00:41:42.090 --> 00:41:45.280
In fact, they're every bit as
strong as these bonds, but

00:41:45.280 --> 00:41:45.820
there's a fourth.

00:41:45.820 --> 00:41:47.370
I said, you always
have to find four

00:41:47.370 --> 00:41:48.230
struts off the carbons.

00:41:48.230 --> 00:41:49.910
So where's the fourth strut?

00:41:49.910 --> 00:41:52.460
It's the pi bond that comes
out of the board.

00:41:52.460 --> 00:41:55.710
So there's a pi bond here and
a pi bond here and a pi bond

00:41:55.710 --> 00:41:57.680
here and what we're going to
learn later is that these

00:41:57.680 --> 00:41:58.930
things are delocalized.

00:42:02.100 --> 00:42:06.000
Because of the spacing here, the
electrons can form a bond

00:42:06.000 --> 00:42:09.150
here that then forms a bond
here, but it can actually

00:42:09.150 --> 00:42:11.710
resonate in such a way that
the electrons can move

00:42:11.710 --> 00:42:15.100
everywhere throughout the
crystal of graphite and this

00:42:15.100 --> 00:42:18.860
is what gives graphite its
electrical conductivity,

00:42:18.860 --> 00:42:20.750
whereas diamond is a
strict insulator.

00:42:20.750 --> 00:42:24.370
So these are very strong bonds
in the plane, but not between

00:42:24.370 --> 00:42:26.800
planes, which gives graphite
its lubricity.

00:42:26.800 --> 00:42:29.430
It's a dry-lock lubricant
and so on.

00:42:29.430 --> 00:42:30.170
OK.

00:42:30.170 --> 00:42:31.870
So this is very good.

00:42:31.870 --> 00:42:36.590
So we have a mix of sigma
and pi bonds.

00:42:39.650 --> 00:42:45.860
And it's an absorber
and it's dark.

00:42:45.860 --> 00:42:49.310
It's an absorber so it appears
black, whereas this diamond is

00:42:49.310 --> 00:42:50.580
transparent to visible light.

00:42:54.650 --> 00:42:57.860
And if you look in your book,
this is all categorized for

00:42:57.860 --> 00:43:00.420
you, everything that we've
done here with VSPER.

00:43:00.420 --> 00:43:00.780
All right.

00:43:00.780 --> 00:43:02.210
Look at this.

00:43:02.210 --> 00:43:04.670
All nice big system.

00:43:04.670 --> 00:43:05.370
OK.

00:43:05.370 --> 00:43:08.940
So here's diamond, which I was
trying to draw over here, four

00:43:08.940 --> 00:43:10.390
struts sp3 hybridized.

00:43:10.390 --> 00:43:14.560
this is graphite sp2, and these
are pi bonds in between.

00:43:14.560 --> 00:43:16.010
OK.

00:43:16.010 --> 00:43:20.590
Now suppose this fellow asks
this girl out, and things get

00:43:20.590 --> 00:43:21.940
serious and they get--

00:43:21.940 --> 00:43:24.380
I'm going to use an adverb
here-- really serious and he

00:43:24.380 --> 00:43:27.540
decides maybe he wants to make
a commitment and he wants to

00:43:27.540 --> 00:43:31.350
buy her a ring, an engagement
ring, and the custom is that

00:43:31.350 --> 00:43:34.180
the engagement ring
has a stone in it.

00:43:34.180 --> 00:43:38.570
Now being an MIT student, he
knows that he wants to have

00:43:38.570 --> 00:43:40.850
symbolism in that stone.

00:43:40.850 --> 00:43:45.540
Now the custom is to get
diamond, but it turns out that

00:43:45.540 --> 00:43:49.030
if you look carefully, the
stable form of carbon at room

00:43:49.030 --> 00:43:51.050
temperature and atmospheric
pressure is not

00:43:51.050 --> 00:43:53.270
diamond, it's graphite.

00:43:53.270 --> 00:43:57.270
So if he wants to give his
love this stone that

00:43:57.270 --> 00:44:02.390
symbolizes eternal commitment,
wouldn't he choose the stable

00:44:02.390 --> 00:44:05.910
form and not the one that's
metastable and doesn't

00:44:05.910 --> 00:44:08.380
represent the natural state
at room temperature?

00:44:11.010 --> 00:44:12.000
That's the truth.

00:44:12.000 --> 00:44:13.740
That's the truth.

00:44:13.740 --> 00:44:15.120
Graphite is the stable form.

00:44:15.120 --> 00:44:18.180
I leave it up to the young man
to persuade the young lady

00:44:18.180 --> 00:44:23.120
that the gemstone is going
to have graphite

00:44:23.120 --> 00:44:25.730
in it and not diamond.

00:44:25.730 --> 00:44:26.210
OK.

00:44:26.210 --> 00:44:29.480
Now something very interesting
happened.

00:44:29.480 --> 00:44:32.650
What I wanted to play for you as
you're leaving today is an

00:44:32.650 --> 00:44:35.580
old Beatles song, Lucy in
the Sky With Diamonds.

00:44:35.580 --> 00:44:36.950
And what happened--

00:44:36.950 --> 00:44:39.810
before I get to it, what
happened was-- and this is

00:44:39.810 --> 00:44:43.630
even in today's Le Tech if you
look on the second page, "New

00:44:43.630 --> 00:44:47.840
Fossil Skeleton from africa
Predates Lucy." It was just

00:44:47.840 --> 00:44:48.570
discovered.

00:44:48.570 --> 00:44:49.270
I'm not kidding you.

00:44:49.270 --> 00:44:50.500
This isn't a joke.

00:44:50.500 --> 00:44:52.340
I heard this on NPR
last night.

00:44:52.340 --> 00:44:58.240
So it's a female skeleton of a
pre-hominid, 4.4 million years

00:44:58.240 --> 00:45:00.980
old, which is a million
years older than Lucy.

00:45:00.980 --> 00:45:05.880
Lucy was discovered in
Ethiopia in 1974 and

00:45:05.880 --> 00:45:08.820
considered to be 3.18
million years old.

00:45:08.820 --> 00:45:12.360
This new one is 4.4 million
years old, about four feet

00:45:12.360 --> 00:45:18.070
tall, and it just turns the
clock even farther back.

00:45:18.070 --> 00:45:20.240
The interesting thing
is the name.

00:45:20.240 --> 00:45:24.290
How did the skeleton
discovered in 1974

00:45:24.290 --> 00:45:25.920
get the name Lucy?

00:45:25.920 --> 00:45:27.050
Interesting story.

00:45:27.050 --> 00:45:29.670
There were two American
archaeologists that were head

00:45:29.670 --> 00:45:34.650
of the team that did the dig,
and they were so excited the

00:45:34.650 --> 00:45:38.330
night they found this
pre-hominid skeleton.

00:45:38.330 --> 00:45:41.890
They knew it was a female, and
they hadn't dated it yet, but

00:45:41.890 --> 00:45:45.440
they knew that it was roughly
way, way back, but it was

00:45:45.440 --> 00:45:46.630
definitely female.

00:45:46.630 --> 00:45:49.740
So they were back at the
campfire, kicking back,

00:45:49.740 --> 00:45:54.470
drinking, probably heavily, and
singing songs, and one of

00:45:54.470 --> 00:45:56.950
the songs they were singing
was Lucy in the Sky With

00:45:56.950 --> 00:46:02.380
Diamonds and that night, they
named the skeleton Lucy.

00:46:02.380 --> 00:46:04.100
But the story doesn't
end there.

00:46:04.100 --> 00:46:07.680
Where did this Lucy in the Sky
With Diamonds come from?

00:46:07.680 --> 00:46:09.800
John Lennon, one of the--

00:46:09.800 --> 00:46:11.800
you may have heard of this group
or not, but there was

00:46:11.800 --> 00:46:13.130
this group called The Beatles.

00:46:13.130 --> 00:46:16.940
So one of the lead composers
was John Lennon.

00:46:16.940 --> 00:46:20.980
His six-year-old son came home
from school one day with a

00:46:20.980 --> 00:46:24.290
piece of artwork, and the father
asks, what is this?

00:46:24.290 --> 00:46:30.600
He says, it's a painting of my
classmate Lucy, and it was

00:46:30.600 --> 00:46:32.390
Lucy and he had diamonds
in the sky.

00:46:32.390 --> 00:46:34.510
So it was Lucy in the Sky with
Diamonds, and then they wrote

00:46:34.510 --> 00:46:36.360
the song about it.

00:46:36.360 --> 00:46:38.660
The real Lucy just
died this week.

00:46:38.660 --> 00:46:39.450
She had Lupus.

00:46:39.450 --> 00:46:41.700
She died at the age of 46.

00:46:41.700 --> 00:46:46.000
And all of these things have
come together just because we

00:46:46.000 --> 00:46:51.210
had this lesson today about
covalent bonding, which took

00:46:51.210 --> 00:46:54.990
us to this, which then took us
to Ethiopia, which then takes

00:46:54.990 --> 00:46:56.390
this up here.

00:46:56.390 --> 00:46:58.910
and so with that, I think
we'll go for an early

00:46:58.910 --> 00:47:02.470
dismissal, and I'll wish
you a pleasant weekend.

